               Counterfeiting and making 20 Shillings of False and Unlawful Metal, to the likeness and similitude of the proper Coin of this Kingdom
            </rs>, which he did on the <rs id="t16940830-20-cd88" type="crimeDate">28th of August</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t16940830-20-off87 t16940830-20-cd88"></join>. The Prisoner's Garret being search'd in <placeName id="t16940830-20-crimeloc89">Grays-Inn Lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t16940830-20-crimeloc89" type="placeName" value="Grays-Inn Lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t16940830-20-crimeloc89" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t16940830-20-off87 t16940830-20-crimeloc89"></join>, he was found sitting in a Chair, rubbing an Halfcrown between his Fingers, with a certain Powder the Clippers have to make it smooth. There were several other Halfcrowns that lay by him ready done, which were produced in Court; besides a Coining Press, Stamps, Screws, Molds and Flasks, with melting Pots, Scissers, and all Instruments fit for Coining, as also several Halfcrowns that were made of False Metal. This was full Evidence; and he was heard to say, that he was undone, and desired the Constable to be kind to him, for, Lord have mercy upon me, I am a dead man, he says. There was a melting Pot in the Room, and a Fire, and all things lay in a posture fit for working. The Prisoner alleg'd in his defence, that the things did not belong to him, nor the Room, but to one William Peny his Brother's Son, who was gone away. He having nothing else to say, was found <rs id="t16940830-20-verdict90" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16940830-20-verdict90" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               guilty
            </rs> of both Clipping and Coining.</p>
